definitions.bareActText:
2. In these rules, unless the context otherwise requires,-

(a) "Act" means the Digital Personal Data Protection Act, 2023;

(b) "Board" means the Data Protection Board of India established under section 18 of the Act;

(c) "Consent Manager" means a person registered with the Board to provide a platform for Data Principals to give, manage, review, and withdraw their consent;

(d) "Data Fiduciary" has the same meaning as assigned to it in clause (i) of sub-section (1) of section 2 of the Act;

(e) "Data Principal" has the same meaning as assigned to it in clause (j) of sub-section (1) of section 2 of the Act;

(f) "Data Processor" has the same meaning as assigned to it in clause (k) of sub-section (1) of section 2 of the Act;

(g) "Personal Data Breach" means any unauthorised processing of personal data or accidental disclosure, acquisition, sharing, use, alteration, destruction of or loss of access to personal data that compromises the confidentiality, integrity or availability of personal data;

(h) "Significant Data Fiduciary" has the same meaning as assigned to it in section 15 of the Act.

subsections.bareActText:
7. (1) Every Significant Data Fiduciary shall:

(a) appoint a Data Protection Officer who shall be responsible for ensuring compliance with the Act and these rules;

(b) conduct a Data Protection Impact Assessment in respect of processing that involves high risk to the rights of Data Principals;

(c) submit to the Board, within such period as may be prescribed, a report containing such information as may be specified by the Board regarding compliance with the Act and these rules.

(2) The Data Protection Officer shall be based in India and shall be accessible to Data Principals for exercising their rights under the Act.

(3) The Data Protection Impact Assessment shall include:

(a) description of the processing operations;

(b) assessment of the necessity and proportionality of the processing;

(c) assessment of the risks to the rights of Data Principals; and

(d) measures envisaged to address the risks.

14. (1) A person may apply to the Board for registration as a Consent Manager.

(2) The Board may register a person as a Consent Manager if it is satisfied that:

(a) the person has the technical and organizational capabilities to provide consent management services;

(b) the person has implemented appropriate security measures;

(c) the person will comply with the standards and procedures prescribed by the Board.

(3) A Consent Manager shall:

(a) provide a platform for Data Principals to give, manage, review, and withdraw consent;

(b) maintain records of consent given, managed, or withdrawn through its platform;

(c) ensure that consent is communicated to the relevant Data Fiduciaries in a secure manner;

(d) comply with such other requirements as may be prescribed by the Board.

16. (1) These rules shall come into force on the date of their publication in the Official Gazette.

(2) Notwithstanding sub-rule (1), the following provisions shall come into force:

(a) immediately upon publication: Rules 1 to 6, 11, 12, and 13;

(b) twelve months after publication: Rules 7, 8, 9, and 10;

(c) eighteen months after publication: Rules 14 and 15.

(3) The Central Government may, by notification, modify the dates specified in sub-rule (2).
